{"id":"2206.01212","submitter":"Giovanni Maria Tomaselli","authors":"Daniel Baumann, Gianfranco Bertone, John Stout, Giovanni Maria\n  Tomaselli","title":"Sharp Signals of Boson Clouds in Black Hole Binary Inspirals","comments":"6 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 128, 221102 (2022)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.128.221102","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc hep-ph hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Gravitational waves (GWs) are an exciting new probe of physics beyond the\nstandard models of gravity and particle physics. One interesting possibility is\nprovided by the so-called \"gravitational atom,\" wherein a superradiant\ninstability spontaneously forms a cloud of ultralight bosons around a rotating\nblack hole. The presence of these boson clouds affects the dynamics of black\nhole binary inspirals and their associated GW signals. In this Letter, we show\nthat the binary companion can induce transitions between bound and unbound\nstates of the cloud, effectively \"ionizing\" it, analogous to the photoelectric\neffect in atomic physics. The orbital energy lost in this process can overwhelm\nthe losses due to GW emission, so that ionization drives the inspiral rather\nthan merely perturbing it. We show that the ionization power contains sharp\nfeatures that lead to distinctive \"kinks\" in the evolution of the emitted GW\nfrequency. These discontinuities are a unique signature of the boson cloud and\nobserving them would not only constitute a detection of the ultralight boson\nitself, but also provide direct information about its mass and the state of the\ncloud.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 2 Jun 2022 18:00:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-06-06"}
